word_summaries_chapter_94:
  94:1:1:"The first word of verse (94:1) is divided into 2 morphological segments. An interrogative <i class=\"ab\">alif</i> and negative particle. The prefixed <i class=\"ab\">alif</i> is an interrogative particle used to form a question and is usually translated as \"is\", \"are\", or \"do\"."
  94:1:2:"The second word of verse (94:1) is an imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>). The verb is first person plural and is in the jussive mood (<span class=\"at\">مجزوم</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">shīn rā ḥā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ش ر ح</span>)."
  94:1:3:"The third word of verse (94:1) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and personal pronoun. The prefixed preposition <i class=\"ab\">lām</i> is usually translated as \"for\". The personal pronoun is second person masculine singular. Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  94:1:4:"The fourth word of verse (94:1) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A noun and possessive pronoun. The noun is masculine and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ṣād dāl rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ص د ر</span>). The attached possessive pronoun is second person masculine singular."
  94:2:1:"The first word of verse (94:2) is divided into 3 morphological segments. A conjunction, verb and subject pronoun. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is first person plural. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">wāw ḍād ʿayn</i> (<span class=\"at\">و ض ع</span>). The suffix (<span class=\"at\">نا</span>) is an attached subject pronoun."
  94:2:2:"The second word of verse (94:2) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and object pronoun. The attached object pronoun is second person masculine singular. Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  94:2:3:"The third word of verse (94:2) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A noun and possessive pronoun. The noun is feminine and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">wāw zāy rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">و ز ر</span>). The attached possessive pronoun is second person masculine singular."
  94:3:1:"The first word of verse (94:3) is a masculine singular relative pronoun."
  94:3:2:"The second word of verse (94:3) is a form IV perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>). The verb is third person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">nūn qāf ḍād</i> (<span class=\"at\">ن ق ض</span>)."
  94:3:3:"The third word of verse (94:3) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A noun and possessive pronoun. The noun is masculine and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ẓā hā rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ظ ه ر</span>). The attached possessive pronoun is second person masculine singular."
  94:4:1:"The first word of verse (94:4) is divided into 3 morphological segments. A conjunction, verb and subject pronoun. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is first person plural. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā fā ʿayn</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر ف ع</span>). The suffix (<span class=\"at\">نا</span>) is an attached subject pronoun."
  94:4:2:"The second word of verse (94:4) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and personal pronoun. The prefixed preposition <i class=\"ab\">lām</i> is usually translated as \"for\". The personal pronoun is second person masculine singular. Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  94:4:3:"The third word of verse (94:4) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A verbal noun and possessive pronoun. The verbal noun is masculine and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The verbal noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">dhāl kāf rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ذ ك ر</span>). The attached possessive pronoun is second person masculine singular."
  94:5:1:"The first word of verse (94:5) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and accusative particle. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">fa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The accusative particle belongs to a special group of words known as <i class=\"ab\">inna</i> and her sisters (<span class=\"at\">ان واخواتها</span>)."
  94:5:2:"The second word of verse (94:5) is a preposition."
  94:5:3:"The third word of verse (94:5) is a masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn sīn rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع س ر</span>)."
  94:5:4:"The fourth word of verse (94:5) is an indefinite masculine noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">yā sīn rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ي س ر</span>)."
  94:6:1:"The first word of verse (94:6) is an accusative particle which belongs to a special group of words known as <i class=\"ab\">inna</i> and her sisters (<span class=\"at\">ان واخواتها</span>)."
  94:6:2:"The second word of verse (94:6) is a preposition."
  94:6:3:"The third word of verse (94:6) is a masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn sīn rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع س ر</span>)."
  94:6:4:"The fourth word of verse (94:6) is an indefinite masculine noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">yā sīn rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ي س ر</span>)."
  94:7:1:"The first word of verse (94:7) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A resumption particle and time adverb. The connective particle <i class=\"ab\">fa</i> is usually translated as \"then\" or \"so\" and is used to indicate a sequence of events."
  94:7:2:"The second word of verse (94:7) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A verb and subject pronoun. The perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is second person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">fā rā ghayn</i> (<span class=\"at\">ف ر غ</span>). The suffix (<span class=\"at\">التاء</span>) is an attached subject pronoun."
  94:7:3:"The third word of verse (94:7) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A result particle and verb. The result particle <i class=\"ab\">fa</i> is usually translated as \"then\" or \"so\" and is used to indicate the result of a condition. The imperative verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل أمر</span>) is second person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">nūn ṣād bā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ن ص ب</span>)."
  94:8:1:"The first word of verse (94:8) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and preposition. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\"."
  94:8:2:"The second word of verse (94:8) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A noun and possessive pronoun. The noun is masculine and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā bā bā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر ب ب</span>). The attached possessive pronoun is second person masculine singular."
  94:8:3:"The third word of verse (94:8) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and verb. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">fa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The imperative verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل أمر</span>) is second person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā ghayn bā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر غ ب</span>)."